display="inline"><![CDATA[b\in  B]]></fr:tex>. Thus if we consider the subset <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[U\subseteq  B]]></fr:tex> spanned by elements of the form <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[f{\mathopen {}\left (a\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>, we should then get a <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00KR.xml"
addr="jms-00KR"
title="Bijection">bijection</fr:link> from <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex>as each <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[b\in  U]]></fr:tex> comes from a <fr:em>unique</fr:em> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a\in  A]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>

 <fr:p>Therefore, choosing an <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00MO.xml"
addr="jms-00MO"
title="Injection">injection</fr:link> amounts to making <fr:em>two</fr:em> independent choices: first we choose a subset of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> that is in <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00KR.xml"
addr="jms-00KR"
title="Bijection">bijection</fr:link> with <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, and then we choose a <fr:em>specific</fr:em> <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00KR.xml"
addr="jms-00KR"
title="Bijection">bijection</fr:link> from <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> to that subset. The number of such subsets is precisely <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathord {\#}{B}\choose  \mathord {\#}{A}]]></fr:tex>, and we have already seen in <fr:ref
addr="jms-00KT"
taxon="Proposition" /> that the number of such bijections is the factorial <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[{\mathopen {}\left (\mathord {\#}{A}!\right )\mathclose {}}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>

 <fr:p>Of course, if there is no subset of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> equinumerous with <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, then there can be no <fr:link
type="local"
href="jms-00MO.xml"
addr="jms-00MO"
title="Injection">injection</fr:link>.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
 
